%S A097478 9,17,35,53,85,117
%N A097478 Atomic numbers of halogens in the periodic table.
%C A097478 The halogens are all on the second rightmost column of the periodic table. (The rightmost column belongs to the noble gases.) - _Alonso del Arte_, Apr 26 2011
%C A097478 From _Daniel Forgues_, Jul 12-13 2015: (Start)
%C A097478 Hydrogen is not a halogen: although its valence shell is one electron short of being full (like the halogens), it has only one valence electron (like the alkali metals).
%C A097478 Halogens: 9: fluorine (F), 17: chlorine (Cl), 35: bromine (Br), 53: iodine (I), 85: astatine (At) and 117: Ununseptium (Uus).
%C A097478 Astatine: behaves chemically like iodine, highly radioactive.
%C A097478 Ununseptium: metal (...then not halogen?), highly radioactive. (End)
%D A097478 Monica Halka and Brian Nordstrom, Halogens and Noble Gases, Facts On File (2010), Part 1: The Halogens.
